08.Unit Standards
¶

Primary Standards¶

Primary unit standards are precise definitions of physical variables.

Some examples of standards in everyday use are:

  • United States Customary Units (USCS or USC)
  • Imperial Units
  • English Units
  • English Engineering Units
  • International System of Units (SI)

The seven different SI primary standards are:

  • Time - second ($s$)
  • Mass - kilogram ($kg$)
  • Amount of substance - mole ($mol$)
  • Luminous intensity - candela ($cd$)
  • Temperature - Kelvin ($K$)
  • Current - ampere ($A$)
  • Length - meter ($m$)

As of May 20th, 2019, the primary standards for the SI system were updated.

The following changes were made.

  • 4 of the 7 were redefined; $kg$, $A$, $K$, and $mol$
  • 2 were corrected; $m$, and $cd$

Time¶

The second is defined as $$ 1s \equiv \frac{9,192,631,770}{\Delta \nu_{Cs}} $$

where $ \Delta \nu_{Cs} $ is the frequency of the radiation corresponding to the transition between two hyperfine levels of the ground state of cesium-133 atom.

Figure 1: The FOCS 1

The FOCS 1 started in 2004 and has an uncertainty of $1s$ in 30 million years ($9.46728\times10^{14}s$).

Mass¶

The old definition is

  1. The kilogram is the mass of a platinum-iridium cylinder called "International Prototype Kilogram" (IPK), sometimes called Le Grand K, kept at the International Bureau of Weights and Measurements in France.
Figure 2: The International Prototype Kilogram
Figure 3: IPK vs Sister Copies
  • All sister copies gained mass
  • The IPK is losing mass
  • A combination of both

The new definition is

$$ 1kg \equiv \frac{\left( 299,792,458 \right)^2}{\left( 6.62607015 \times 10^{-34} \right)\left( 9,192,631,770 \right)} \frac{h \Delta \nu_{Cs}}{c^2} $$

where

  • $h$ is the Planck constant
  • $ \Delta \nu_{Cs} $ is as defined previously
  • $ c $ is the speed of light in a vacuum

Amount Of Substance¶

The old definition is

  1. The mole is the amount of substance of a system containing as many elementary entities as atoms in $ 0.012 kg$ of carbon-12.
Figure 4: Carbon-12 Isotope

The new definition is

$$ 1 mol \equiv \frac{6.02214076 \times 10^{23}}{N_A} $$

where $ N_A$ is the Avogadro constant.

Figure 5: Amedeo Avogadro

Luminous Intensity¶

The old definition is

  1. The luminous intensity, in a given direction, of a source that emits monochromatic radiation of frequency $ 540 \times 10^2 Hz$ and of which the radiant intensity in that direction is $ \frac{1}{683} \frac{W}{sr} $.
Figure 6: Steradian

The new definition is

$$ 1 cd \equiv \frac{K_{cd} h c \Delta \nu_{Cs}}{\left( 683 \right)\left( 6.62607015 \times 10^{-34} \right)\left( 299,792,458 \right)\left( 9,192,631,770 \right)} $$

where $K_{cd}$ is the luminous efficacy of monochromatic radiation of frequency $540 \times 10^2 Hz$ and all the other constants are as previously described.

Temperature¶

The old definition is

  1. The Kelvin is $ 1 / 273.16 $ of the triple point of water.
Figure 7: Water Phase Diagram with Triple Point Location

The new definition is

$$ 1 K \equiv \frac{1.380649 \times 10^{-23}}{\left( 6.62607015 \times 10^{-34} \right)\left( 9,192,631,770 \right)} \frac{h \Delta \nu_{Cs}}{k} $$

where $k$ is the Boltzman constant and all other constants are as previously defined.

Current¶

The old definition is

  1. The ampere is the constant current that occurs in two straight parallel conductors of infinite length, and negligible circular sections placed $1$ meter apart in a vacuum producing a force equal to $2 \times 10^{-7} N/m$.
Figure 8: Old Ampere Definition

The red arrows show the flow of electricity through each conductor

The blue arrows show the force of attraction between the two conductors

The new definition is

$$ 1 A \equiv \frac{e \Delta \nu_{Cs}}{\left( 1.602176634 \times 10^{-19} \right)\left( 9,192,631,770 \right)} $$

where $e$ is the elementary charge and $\Delta \nu_{Cs}$ is as previously defined.

Length¶

At one time it was

  1. One ten-millionth of the distance between the north pole and the equator at Paris's longitude.
Figure 9: Platinum and iridium prototype meter stick

The old definition is

  1. The meter is the length of the path traveled by light in a vacuum during a duration of $1/299,792,458$ of a second.

The new definition is

$$ 1 m \equiv \frac{9,192,631,770}{299,792,458} \frac{c}{\Delta \nu_{Cs}} $$

Terminology of Standards¶

A fixed standard is one that cannot be reproduced in a lab

A reproducible standard is one that may be reproduced in a properly equipped lab

Secondary standards are standards that have been compared to a primary standard at some point in time
